         <abstract>
            <p>The effects of exogenous shocks in the monetary growth rate on nominal prices and interest rates are analyzed. A representative-individual rational-expectations framework is adopted, and a demand for money is generated by entering money in the utility function. The effects of monetary shocks on inflation and interest rates are shown to depend on the autocorrelation of the monetary growth rate: for example, under serial independence the inflation rate equals the monetary growth rate and the nominal interest rate is nonrandom, while under positive (negative) autocorrelation the nominal interest rate is affected positively (negatively) by positive growth rate shocks.</p>
         </abstract>
